Pointers vs Iterators

The main differences between an iterator and a pointer in C++ are:

Type of data they handle:
        Pointer: A pointer is a memory address that refers directly to a variable or memory location.
        Iterator: An iterator is an abstraction, an object that points to an element within a 
		container (like a vector, list, etc.). 
			   It provides an interface to traverse the container without directly exposing memory addresses.

Behavior:
        Pointer: Pointers perform arithmetic operations like addition and subtraction directly on 
			memory addresses.
        Iterator: Iterators provide similar traversal behavior but are more generalized and abstract. 
				They are not limited to contiguous memory like pointers (e.g., linked lists have non-contiguous memory, 
				and iterators work well there).

Container Compatibility:
        Pointer: Only works well with arrays or contiguous blocks of memory.
        Iterator: Works with any STL container (std::vector, std::list, std::deque, etc.), even those that 
	do not use contiguous memory.

Safety and Flexibility:
        Pointer: Can easily lead to issues like accessing invalid memory (dangling pointers).
        Iterator: Provides a more controlled way to traverse containers and avoids 
			some low-level memory management issues.

In short, pointers are low-level memory addresses, 
while iterators abstract the traversal of elements in various types of containers in C++.
